04830nam a22006375i 9781477302767DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211975txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773027677 a10.7560/7751382doi  a(DE-B1597)586832  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHD1531.P4bH35 1975 7aPOL0570002bisacsh04a322.209851 aHandelman, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStruggle in the Andes :bPeasant Political Mobilization in Peru /cHoward Handelman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1975  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Peru: A Dual Society -- t3. The Social Structure of the Traditional Sierra -- t4. Social Change and the Breakdown of Traditional Society -- t5. The Peasants Take Their Land -- t6. The Growth of Peasant Federations -- t7. Social Correlates of Peasant Mobilization -- t8. A Theory of Peasant Mobilization -- t9. The Peasantry and the National Political System -- t10. Epilogue: The Peasantry Awaits Agrarian Reform -- tAppendix A. Statistical Data -- tAppendix B. Methods of Data Collection -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA massive land-seizure movement first erupted in Peru in 1958 and spread across the Andean highlands in 1963–1964. Several hundred peasant communities in the Peruvian Andes occupied neighboring haciendas in an attempt to retake lands they felt had been stolen from them over the years. Hacienda peasants also participated in this movement, forming peasant sindicatos (unions) to improve their labor conditions. The land-seizure movement brought with it an upsurge in community political mobilization. Throughout the highlands, village leaders banded together in regional federations, often allying themselves with progressive or radical urban groups. Radical activists from labor unions and university student groups joined with indigenous peasant leaders, breaking down the highland peasantry’s traditional isolation from the political system. Struggle in the Andes is an analysis of the causes and consequences of extensive social and political mobilization among Peru’s peasant population in the 1960s. In addition to describing the growth of the peasant land movement, Howard Handelman investigates the social and economic conditions that contributed to rural unrest. Using data that he collected in forty-one diverse highland communities, Handelman examines the correlates of peasant political activity, concluding that land seizures in the traditional southern sierra had different origins and political implications than did unrest in the more socioeconomically modernized central highlands. The data suggest a model of peasant mobilization that calls into question prevailing scholarly hypotheses on the relationships between modernization, peasant political mobilization, and radicalization. Handelman discusses the land-reform program and the accompanying rural mobilization that was being implemented by Peru’s reformist military regime. Using his model of peasant mobilization, he speculates on the possible effects of the government’s contemporary programs on future peasant political behavior.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAgricultural laborersxLabor unionszPeru. 0aAgricultural laborersxPolitical activityzPeru. 0aAgricultural laborers-Political activity-Peru. 0aLand reformzPeru. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477302767423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477302767/original  aEBA_BACKALL